 RITHOLTZ: Right.</p><p> WEINSTEIN: They could be multiples of what they are. And the best funds are super disciplined about how they&#39;ve grown. Balyasny lost a lot of capital in 2018. It got down to $6 billion. It took five years to get back up to peak AUM, which is $20 billion now, but they were really disciplined about how they did it. They didn&#39;t just boom, double and triple within a few years. They built their infrastructure, risk management, and hired great PMs to lead these businesses. And that it&#39;s so important because you&#39;ll dilute returns without getting the talent piece right in keeping pace to AUM growth.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: That&#39;s really interesting. So we&#39;re going to talk more about talent in a bit, but I want to go back to some of the things you raised that&#39;s really quite fascinating.</p><p> So it&#39;s obvious. If you&#39;re making a directional bet, or even worse, a leveraged directional bet, and you&#39;re your funds going to suffer. But I&#39;m kind of intrigued by what you said about macro. I know there&#39;s a wide dispersion of performance in macro, but if any year macro should have done well, it was 2022 where if you had the inflation side right, if you had the Fed– –</p><p> WEINSTEIN: They did, they did well in &#39;22.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: They should have crushed it.</p><p> WEINSTEIN: I think the point I was making is, it&#39;s been choppy in that it&#39;s like &#39;22 was good, but then look at &#39;21 and look at &#39;23. So as–</p><p> RITHOLTZ: That&#39;s what you mean by spiky is it&#39;s not consistent over time.</p><p> WEINSTEIN: That&#39;s what I mean by spiky. I mean, an AUM, by the way, has followed that. Brevan Howard at peak was 40 billion, then it drops down to six and change in 2018, and now it&#39;s back up again. But that&#39;s what I mean by spiky, as opposed to an entity, whether it&#39;s a top multi-manager or a top multi-strat that is able to navigate different markets, put up consistent return stream 