out managing your career. Staying put cannot be just the default position.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Is it just inertia? People just get comfortable and don&#39;t want to move?</p><p> WEINSTEIN: I think people get comfortable and they feel like, again, it&#39;s economic loss aversion theory at work. They overweight everything that can go wrong and they really don&#39;t pay attention to if they make a move. They underweight what can go right and they&#39;re just not focused on the dire situation that they&#39;re in.</p><p> And when you&#39;re being deliberate about managing your career, you&#39;re asking, and I&#39;m not suggesting people hop around for the sake of hopping around, but you do need to ask yourself the tough questions at various pivot points. And this isn&#39;t just true for hedge funds, it&#39;s true for any industry. How is my fund or firm performing? How am I evolving? Am I learning the skills I need in order to be effective going forward? Am I on a path to grow? Am I stagnating or am I increasing my value and optionality in the market? Am I being paid fairly?</p><p> And to the extent that they&#39;re not and they&#39;re just literally sticking their head under the covers and not thinking about these things, they really need to ask themselves why that&#39;s the case. It&#39;s the number one reason people flame out. They don&#39;t keep pressing forward, don&#39;t keep improving, don&#39;t keep learning.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So that raises a really interesting question because you&#39;re suggesting that talent should be thinking about more than just salary and equity. There&#39;s a lot of other things they should be looking for. When you&#39;re counseling a superstar to switch funds, what are you telling them that they can get besides just, “Hey, here&#39;s money, and you get some equity in the GP” what&#39;s in it for them?</p><p> WEINSTEIN: I think there&#39;s four main things. One is to be made better, to learn things that they&#39;re not learning where they&#39;re at, which more than ever today is important.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Matters, sure.</p><p> WEINSTEIN: Number two is autonomy. And even if it&#39;s not complete jurisdiction over the portfolio, increased ability to impact the results. Okay? So people should really want that and that sense of agency.</p><p> The second thing is clarity. Not the number per se, that&#39;s important, but clarity around how we get to that number.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Meaning it&#39;s not a crazy calculation. You have an idea each month, each quarter, how you&#39;re personally doing the terms of –</p><p> WEINSTEIN: I&#39;m not saying it has to be. Well, I mean, if you&#39;re on a payout, then yes you do. But even in situations where you don&#39;t have a payout or points in the fund, you have to have clarity around why the founder makes the decisions he does. The most frustrating thing in this industry is for people who perform, who get netted, meaning the founder takes from Peter to pay Paul, and doesn&#39;t reach into his own pocket in order to do that.</p><p> And I was– and the fourth thing, just before I forget, is stability. I&#39;ll come back to compensation. Stability or clarity around compensation. Stability in terms of that you&#39;re not going to get blown out at the slightest misstep. These are the four things that are important to people. And stability that the fund is on solid footing, which increasingly is a more difficult thing given how many funds look today like melting ice cubes.</p><p> But back to compensation, the founder has to be clear on what the P&amp;L is of the fund and how he uses the management fee to the extent that there isn&#39;t a clear formula in terms of how you&#39;re paid. People need to understand why they&#39;re getting paid what they&#39;re getting paid.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So I&#39;m a little confused. You&#39;re a rock star at one fund. You get an enticing offer in another fund and you may not know what your comp is going to look like even if you&#39;re putting up really good numbers. That&#39;s perplexing.</p><p> WEINSTEIN: If you&#39;re sitting at a fund where —</p><p> RITHOLTZ: The guy across the hall is stinking the joint up, you&#39;re not going to get your bonus.</p><p> WEINSTEIN: I mean, let&#39;s just say you put up $200 million, the guy across the hall lost $200 million. There&#39;s no pass-through model. So the founder is zero in terms of a performance fee if all he has is the two of you and he&#39;s allocated capital to you. So is he going to reach into his own pocket to make you whole or not? And if you don&#39;t have a payout that he has to abide by, that can be really frustrating if he doesn&#39;t actually make you, you know.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: I think that would be good for your business, because that guy&#39;s going to be out the door. Hey, I don&#39;t care about who else you&#39;re hiring. If I&#39;m putting up good numbers, I expect you to at least have a conversation with me about, “All right, we&#39;re only going to give you half of what you expected because Bob across the hall blew up.” But I mean, what really happens in those circumstances?</p><p> WEINSTEIN: Well, I mean, I will tell you 2022 was really interesting because I was pleasantly surprised by quite a few examples of founders who did reach into their own pocket to pay their best people like the story I told early on where some of these funds with very big holes still did substantial guarantees to retain their top people for this year and for next year.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Seems long term smart, right?</p><p> WEINSTEIN: Long term smart, although the problem is to the extent those funds continue to lose AUM LPs are redeeming or don&#39;t get and/or don&#39;t get out of those high water marks in some reasonable period of time, that&#39;s not really sustainable.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Well, they could just dissolve and reform, then worry about that later.</p><p> WEINSTEIN: And also, those guarantees are ceilings, and really talented people want to be able to —</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right.</p><p> WEINSTEIN: Have untapped ability to get paid.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Clear skies above, and if they do really well, they expect to get paid really well.</p><p> WEINSTEIN: But Barry, what you&#39;re picking up on, which is correct, is to the extent founders don&#39;t have a pass-through model, meaning everything is out of the management fee and performance fee.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: As opposed to segmenting four different funds and the performance fee goes to each of those individual silos.</p><p> WEINSTEIN: Well, meaning they can pass through the expenses of the fund. So you can pass through the expense of paying that guy who made $200 million. All that should matter to LPs is your net return.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right.</p><p> WEINSTEIN: So a pass-through model is a higher bar because there&#39;s more expenses at the end of the day, but these guys who have that very coveted fee structure are able to have that because their net returns are worthy of it. They have a high enough net return.</p><p> In any event, I do think what talent wants is a pathway where they have more agency over what they do and more control and clarity around how they get paid and just to be made better over time so they continue to evolve.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So let&#39;s flip the question. What are the top hedge funds looking for? It&#39;s got to be more than just P&amp;L. Tell us what the top funds want when they ask you to go find me a superstar in this space.</p><p> WEINSTEIN: Coming up a level, I will tell you I do think funds trip themselves up sometimes in using terms like analyst and PM and partner because those things mean very, have very different definitions depending on who we&#39;re speaking to.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Do they matter at some of the larger hedge funds or are people wearing multiple hats doing the same job?</p><p> WEINSTEIN: What I mean is we define, different founders define those things differently. So I&#39;ll give you an example. We did a search about eight years ago for a well-known single manager, long short equity founder, who&#39;d been around at that point for 20 years and had just had one of his most senior people depart. And what he told me he wanted was a partner. The guy was a partner. He wanted someone who, and he said he&#39;s willing to give this guy substantial points and would operate really as a PM alongside him.</p><p> I want someone who&#39;s going to be able to make decisions with me, help deploy capital, help size, help construct the portfolio, more of a PM than an analyst. And what I said to him is, “There&#39;s no one I can find you that has 20 years of working with you.” And the way that you evolved people, because everyone there was hired basically as a young analyst out of Goldman and then homegrown, he saw what people were capable of. They had wins with him over time, and then he gave them more and more responsibility.</p><p> So to go into the market and basically find what for him would be a stranger and put that person in at a senior level, I knew wasn&#39;t going to work. And in fact, what we ended up doing was putting in — It was a senior person, but it was someone who was less experienced, was really a senior analyst. was happy to have a seat at the table and be able to feed him ideas and over time morph into more of a PM or partner type role.</p><p> But PM means different things even among the multi-managers who do have that, you know, where that title really does mean they&#39;re giving somebody an allocation of capital and that person does have autonomy. In some places a PM is really, really, no, it&#39;s man, it&#39;s always managing capital but it might be a small amount of capital.</p><p> You might start with a paper book. It&#39;s like a mini PM, or a PM with training wheels. And you might be overseeing a very small team to start. In other places, we want somebody who can build a scale business out of the gate and can manage a lot of capital. And by the way, their definition of analysts may be different. There are places where being an analyst almost looks more like a PM. They are managing a significant amount of GMV. They do have a payout on that. Their definition of analysts may look, again, it may look more like mini PMs. So we really need to dig into these things and define what we&#39;re after.</p><p> And I would say for an analyst, that&#39;s idea generation, creativity, independent research, asking the right questions. For a PM, it&#39;s risk management, portfolio construction, hedging, sizing, the ability hopefully to build and manage a team.</p><p> And where we&#39;re looking for someone to build a strategy that&#39;s more like a founder. It&#39;s someone that we can raise capital around, potentially raise a fund around, and of course attract talent and also has a sense of what is needed with respect to technology and operations for their strategy. So different skill sets.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: I was going to say it sounds far more complex than I think a lot of people might assume looking in from the outside. How important is fit? How do you figure out, hey, this square peg is going to fit or won&#39;t fit into that round fund. How do you evaluate personalities on top of all these really challenging skill sets? It sounds like it&#39;s not an easy thing to do.</p><p> WEINSTEIN: There are things we do to see how closely the candidate maps to what we will want them to do. We do case studies, idea pitches, mock portfolios, business plans. Those are all sort of the hoops we have them jump through. But then in addition, we do soft referencing as a firm. If you think of 20 years of meeting with the most talented people at every hedge fund, odds are if you&#39;re a candidate, Barry, I&#39;ve met with five other people from your fund that have a point of view on you. Right? So we very quickly get a 360 on how people think, their velocity of ideas, their response time, when they spot an opportunity, their ability to commit capital, and how they systematize their process so it&#39;s scalable and repeatable.</p><p> These are all the things we&#39;re going to dig into in finding out about people. And I also love it when someone comes in with a clear sense of attribution. I don&#39;t think it&#39;s a great sign if someone has no idea what their P&amp;L is. I get that often it&#39;s not tracked at many funds.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Really? I&#39;m shocked to hear that because —</p><p> WEINSTEIN: Not formally tracked.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: But you could still export your book to an Excel spreadsheet and say, “Here&#39;s where I am.”</p><p> WEINSTEIN: We&#39;re saying the same thing. I expect people to have done that. I expect people to have a clear sense of attribution. To the extent that they don&#39;t, it&#39;s not a good sign, is what I&#39;m saying.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: No, I would not.</p><p> WEINSTEIN: But the best people come in, I mean, honestly, some of them come in with a huge spreadsheet, This is what I&#39;ve contributed. And by the way, here are all the things I wanted to do that the founder didn&#39;t let me do and how I would have performed if they&#39;ve let me.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right.</p><p> WEINSTEIN: Now I&#39;m savvy enough after all these years to know and that if I add a little bit of a grain of salt and if I added up all of the returns of everyone we meet from fund A, B or C, it would probably be north of 300%. So you know, there&#39;s that. But I do think there is still something to a sense of ownership and directional truth.</p><p> And then the final thing I&#39;d say to you is there&#39;s always a leap of faith. I don&#39;t care how much work both sides do, and we do a lot of work to have a strong sense that the person will be successful. There&#39;s always a leap of faith because we&#39;re talking about different founders, different definitions of success and failure, different investing style, different approaches to training and development. And I always tell the clients I&#39;m working with that they have to lead with war stories. They have to lead with all the things that might have gone wrong early on when they recruit someone and how they help that person to get out of a hole and to go on and be successful. Because that&#39;s what&#39;s in the minds of people before they make a leap. What happens when things go south? How will I be treated?</p><p> And founders really need to, or whoever&#39;s doing the recruiting, and this is again any industry, you really need to lead with what constitutes failure. Losing money in and of itself, yes, you fail to make money, but why? How did you get yourself into that situation? So there&#39;s sort of like good failure, which is a learning experience and we think we can improve you, and let&#39;s define what is a situation where we think it actually isn&#39;t the right fit. You need to get people clarity.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Makes sense. A good process will occasionally have a bad outcome and you can&#39;t just assume every good outcome is the result of a good process.</p><p> All right, so I only have you for a few more minutes. Let&#39;s jump to our favorite question that we ask all our guests, starting with what has been keeping you entertained over the past couple of years? What have you been doing either when we were locked down or just out and about revenge traveling?</p><p> WEINSTEIN: Revenge traveling. I took a fantastic trip with my son to Italy last summer.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: I do recall we were talking about that and we didn&#39;t know what was going to happen. There was a couple of variants. We were both talking about traveling last summer. Where&#39;d you go in Italy?</p><p> WEINSTEIN: It&#39;s almost where didn&#39;t we go? We went everywhere. The only places we didn&#39;t go were Puglia. Am I pronouncing that correctly? Soft G, Puglia. And we didn&#39;t go to northern Italy.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So I&#39;ve never been to Lake Como and I want to check that out.</p><p> WEINSTEIN: Phenomenal.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: I haven&#39;t been to Milan, I haven&#39;t been to Modena, which is why I&#39;d love to go.</p><p> WEINSTEIN: I have not been to Modena either. But for two foodies like us, that&#39;s worth hitting.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: I have a friend who did this private tour where instead of staying at hotels, you stay at people&#39;s houses and they cook dinner for you and it&#39;s grandma making the secret family recipe and he said he came home 20 pounds heavier.</p><p> WEINSTEIN: I&#39;m sure.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: It was amazing. Let&#39;s talk about mentors. Who helped to shape your career?</p><p> WEINSTEIN: It&#39;s totally my parents.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Really?</p><p> WEINSTEIN: I had amazing parents.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: What did your parents do?</p><p> WEINSTEIN: My father ran a small insurance brokerage so he was an entrepreneur but small. I mean he was this is your classic first-generation immigrant story.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right.</p><p> WEINSTEIN: My dad did grow up in the States. He was born and raised in Brooklyn, part of what we often term the greatest generation.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right.</p><p> WEINSTEIN: He volunteered to fight World War II. He was an amazingly patriotic person. He was a tail gunner for B-29s. They used to take us out. My parents used to take us out to airfields in the middle of nowhere to look at these old planes. Really hardworking guy. And I listened to all the issues that he would bring home and discuss with my mom, who&#39;s an amazingly smart woman. She can run circles around most people. And she was kind of the CEO of our family. She really pushed us to be our best. She helped my dad. She came here. She was a hidden child during the Holocaust.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Oh really?</p><p> WEINSTEIN: It&#39;s a whole story unto itself. She came to Israel, then her family emigrated to Israel, and then she came to the United States, met my father, and they were, we didn&#39;t have much growing up. They just, they did the best they could in the way of giving us stuff, but there wasn&#39;t really a lot of material wealth that I grew up with, far from, but I had great parents who taught me the importance of, by example, through my father and my mom, just in terms of her wisdom, of constantly pressing forward.</p><p> And, you know, there wasn&#39;t a lot of room for whining in my house. She&#39;s, you know, she was in the Israeli army. She&#39;s tough. She&#39;s strong. My dad, again, great, wonderful man who&#39;s a phenomenal salesperson, but worked super hard. And I admired his resilience. And it was about pushing forward and not giving up. And that, I think, is that grit and perseverance. We don&#39;t really talk too much about that. I actually think it&#39;s one of the most important determinants of someone&#39;s success in life and also professionally.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Grit and perseverance, good qualities to have.</p><p> Let&#39;s talk about books, what are some of your favorites? What are you reading right now?</p><p> WEINSTEIN: Well I love books that are about real life, could be a moment in time like Tom Wolfe type books, maybe the story is quote fiction, but loosely based on things that were happening then. or of course Michael Lewis, which is, those are real stories told in a highly entertaining way. The stuff I&#39;m reading now is courtesy of my 18-year-old son who&#39;s gotten into the habit of buying his mom books that he thinks she might like, and he&#39;s hit it out of the jackpot every time.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Really?</p><p> WEINSTEIN: Yeah, so now, thanks to Jordan, I&#39;m reading, I think it&#39;s called “Ticking Clock.” It&#39;s by Ira Rosen, who was a producer for “60 Minutes,” and he bought me that because he knows I love the movie with “The Insider” with Russell Crowe, which was an expose, of course, on the tobacco industry, but also on the world of journalism. And the book is fascinating. It&#39;s like being in the newsroom. It&#39;s all the intrigue that went on behind the scenes. It&#39;s just– it&#39;s an — and it&#39;s so funny. He&#39;s just– he&#39;s like this reverent, no BS, awesome, engaging storyteller. Phenomenal.</p><p> And then the other book I&#39;m reading that my son got for me is called “The Kings of New York” which is about really the New York skyline and the whole real estate industry. And again, told almost like a thriller in terms of how it unfolded, what all the inside baseball was and the rise and fall of a number of real estate dynasties.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Really quite fascinating. Our final two questions, what sort of advice would you give to a recent college grad who is interested in a career in either hedge funds or talent scouting and recruiting.</p><p> WEINSTEIN: For anyone, the question is why do you want to do that? What is it? And if the answer for anything is because they think it&#39;s lucrative, that&#39;s not a good answer.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right. By the way, I&#39;ve heard that time and again from people sitting in that seat. Hey, if you&#39;re in this game for the money alone, you&#39;re going to be disappointed.</p><p> WEINSTEIN: It&#39;s important to try, if you know what you want to do, that&#39;s great. I have a candidate right now who&#39;s been investing in biotech since he was 13. Yes, and so he knows what he wants to do. And I learned that because I said what you studied in college was really interesting. You were pre-med, which is tough enough, and also studying business. Like how did you know back then? He&#39;s like, I just knew. I knew I wasn&#39;t going to be a doctor. I was fascinated by biotech, but I wanted to come at it from the investing angle.</p><p> To the extent you don&#39;t really know, I think it&#39;s so important to try different things. To your opening questions to me, I didn&#39;t know. And I learned through all of my experiences, what I liked, what I was best at, and just as valuable, what I didn&#39;t like, and what I felt, you know, I wasn&#39;t a natural at.</p><p> I think it&#39;s okay to go on a bit of a journey early on, but you have to be on that journey aggressively. And meaning if what you&#39;re doing is not something that really is singing or speaking to you, you have to keep moving forward till you figure it out.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So purposefully —</p><p> WEINSTEIN: Purposefully, you can then lock in and really build something.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Really interesting. And our final question, what do you know about the world of investing today, hedge funds, talent recruitment that you wish you knew 20 years ago when you first launched IDW?</p><p> WEINSTEIN: I&#39;ll use your word purposefully. It&#39;s really important for founders to manage their team purposefully, meaning you have to give people room to fail, but you also have to cut when it makes sense. And I think a lot of founders are afraid to do that because how will it look to LPs? It&#39;s uncomfortable to have to do those, to have to manage people out. What will it do to our culture? But a killer culturally is to be someplace where it becomes a hotbed for mediocrity.</p><p> And so —</p><p> RITHOLTZ: A hotbed for mediocrity, meaning you just start accumulating key players.</p><p> WEINSTEIN: You just start accumulating deadwood. And it becomes, and I hear this time and again where people say, you know, where they haven&#39;t really been paid that well, well, there&#39;s this kind of smoothing effect that goes on at our firm where maybe I&#39;m not paid as well as I should be, but in down, you know, when things don&#39;t go that well at the firm, I also am not hit as hard perhaps as other places.</p><p> And I said, can we take a step back and look at your personal P&amp;L history? For the most part, you&#39;ve been a rock star every year you&#39;ve been there.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Why you hedging —</p><p> WEINSTEIN: Why on earth are you giving yourself an artificial ceiling here? And why are you, for someone who can never put up the goods, that&#39;s a great paradigm. Why is it for you? And so I think again, it all comes back to being front-footed as talent, but also as an institution in managing for growth aggressively.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Ilana, thank you for being so generous with your time. We have been speaking with Ilana Weinstein. She is the founder of the IDW Group and is known as one of the most powerful women in the world of hedge funds.</p><p> If you enjoyed this conversation, well, be sure and check out any of the previous 500 or so we&#39;ve done over the past nine years. You can find those at YouTube, iTunes, Spotify, wherever you get your favorite podcast from. Sign up for my daily reading list at ritholtz.com. Follow me on Twitter for as long as Twitter is here @Ritholtz. Follow all of the Bloomberg family of pods @podcast. I would be remiss if I did not thank the crack team of experts who helped put this conversation together each week. Paris Wald is my producer. Samantha Danziger is my audio engineer. Atika Valbrun is my project manager. Sean Russo is my researcher.</p><p> I&#39;m Barry Ritholtz. You&#39;ve been listening to Masters in Business on Bloomberg Radio.</p><p></p><p style="text-align: center;"> ~~~ </p><p></p><p><iframe style="width: 100%; max-width: 660px; overflow: hidden; background: transparent;" src="https://embed.podcasts.apple.com/us/podcast/masters-in-business/id730188152" height="450" frameborder="0" sandbox="allow-forms allow-popups allow-same-origin allow-scripts allow-storage-access-by-user-activation allow-top-navigation-by-user-activation" data-mce-fragment="1"></iframe></p><p> The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://ritholtz.com/2023/07/transcript-ilana-weinstein-2/">Transcript: Ilana Weinstein</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://ritholtz.com">The Big Picture</a> .</p> ;
